  m_Name: Descending_pectoral_muscle_Superficial_pectoral.L
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ModelPartDataSO
  id: Descending_pectoral_muscle_Superficial_pectoral.L
  partName: Descending pectoral muscle Superficial pectoral Left
  descriptionChunks:
  - The left descending superficial pectoral muscle is situated along the cranial
    chest region of the canine body and forms part of the superficial pectoral group.
    Originating from the sternum and attaching to the humerus, it functions primarily
    to adduct the forelimb and stabilize the shoulder during movement.
  - This muscle contributes to maintaining balanced limb positioning and controlled
    forelimb motion during walking, running, and turning activities. It also assists
    in drawing the limb inward toward the body while supporting posture and weight-bearing
    stability. Coordinated action with surrounding chest muscles improves locomotor
    efficiency.
